05210nam a22006975i 9780520954069DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209540697 a10.1525/97805209540692doi  a(DE-B1597)519152  a(OCoLC)815651151  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHN110.5.A8bP665 2016 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a303.409822300aInstitutions Count :bTheir Role and Significance in Latin American Development /ced. by Alejandro Portes, Lori D. Smith. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Institutions and Development: A Conceptual Reanalysis -- t2. The Comparative Study of Institutions: The “Institutional Turn” in Development Studies: A Review -- t3. Institutional Change and Development in Argentina -- t4. Institutional Change and Development in Chilean Market Society -- t5. The Colombian Paradox: A Thick Institutionalist Analysis -- t6. Development Opportunities: Politics, the State, and Institutions in the Dominican Republic in the Twenty-First Century -- t7. The Uneven and Paradoxical Development of Mexico’s Institutions -- t8. Conclusion: The Comparative Analysis of the Role of Institutions in National Development -- tAppendix: Investigators -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat leads to national progress? The growing consensus in the social sciences is that neither capital flows, nor the savings rate, nor diffuse values are the key, but that it lies in the quality of a nation’s institutions. This book is the first comparative study of how real institutions affect national development. It seeks to examine and deepen this insight through a systematic study of institutions in five Latin American countries and how they differ within and across nations. Postal systems, stock exchanges, public health services and others were included in the sample, all studied with the same methodology. The country chapters present detailed results of this empirical exercise for each individual country. The introductory chapters present the theoretical framework and research methodology for the full study. The summary results of this ambitious study presented in the concluding chapter draw comparisons across countries and discuss what these results mean for national development in Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspectszLatin America. 0aInstitutional economics. 0aPublic administrationzLatin America. 0aSocial institutions - Latin America. 0aSocial institutionszLatin America. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aBrieba, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastellani, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrimson, Alejandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLozano, Wilfredo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPortes, Alejandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPortes, Alejandro, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRodríguez-Garavito, César, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoig, Alexandre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Lori D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Lori D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVelasco, José Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aW